Data Normalization & TF_IDF Process¶

Trimming¶

  • We removed the white space, punctuation, numbers and Special Character

TFID Generation & Print¶

  • tf_idf function will result the all TF-IDF features and print_tf_idf function will display the results in elegant way
In [456]:
# Taken from Gensim preparators
RE_PUNCT = re.compile(r'([%s])+' % re.escape(string.punctuation), re.UNICODE)
RE_NUMERIC = re.compile(r"[0-9]+", re.UNICODE)
RE_NONALPHA = re.compile(r"\W", re.UNICODE)
RE_WHITESPACE = re.compile(r"(\s)+", re.UNICODE)
MIN_LENGTH = 3

# Function definition

def normalise(s):
    if s is None or s is np.nan:
        return ""
    s = s.lower()
    s = RE_PUNCT.sub(" ", s)
    s = RE_WHITESPACE.sub(" ", s)
    s = RE_NUMERIC.sub("", s)
    s = ' '.join([w for w in s.split() if len(w)>=MIN_LENGTH])
    s = RE_NONALPHA.sub(" ", s)
    return s

def tf_idf(vectors: spmatrix, i: int):
    tf_max = vectors[i].data.max()
    tokens = []
    for wi, val in zip(vectors[i].indices, 
                       vectors[i].data):
        
        token = inverse_vocab[wi][0]
        unique_tokens = vectors[i].getnnz()
        token_cnt_global = inverse_vocab[wi][1]
        tf = val
        tf_norm = 0.5+0.5*(tf/tf_max)
        token_n_docs = vectors.T[wi].getnnz()
        idf = np.log(vectors.shape[0]/token_n_docs)
        tokens.append((token, wi, token_cnt_global, tf, token_n_docs, idf, tf*idf, tf_norm*idf))
    return sorted(tokens, key=lambda t: t[7], reverse=True)

def print_tf_idf(vectors:spmatrix, i: int, limit=None):
    print('TOKEN       | TOKEN CNT | TF | TF_normed | IDF | TF_IDF | TF_IDF_normed')
    for t, wi, tcg, tc, tnd, i, ti, tni in tf_idf(vectors, i)[:limit]:
        print(f'{t:<15} | {wi} | {tcg} | {tc} | {tnd} | {i:.4f} | {ti:.4f} | {tni:.4f}')

Dataset=pd.read_csv("E:\Techi\Courses\Masters in Data Science\Courses\Text Visualization\Data sets\Trip Advisor\hotels\data\\test", names=['Date','Title','Content'], delimiter="\t", index_col=3, encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
Dataset["City"]="Test"
Dataset.reset_index()
for city in Cities :
    print("Started : "+city)
    for i in os.listdir(DataPath+city+"\\"):
        try :
            Dataset2=pd.read_csv(DataPath+city+"\\"+i, names=['Date','Title','Content'], delimiter="\t", index_col=3, encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
            Dataset2.reset_index()
            Dataset2["City"]=city
            Dataset2["Hotel"]=i
            Dataset=pd.concat([Dataset,Dataset2],ignore_index=True,axis=0, sort=True)
        except :
            print(city+"\\"+i+" file is corrupted")
    print("Completed : "+city)

Low Rated Hotels (< 3.5)¶

Due to the above reason, we took low rated hostel reviews and built the same graph. we have choosed below hotels which are having less than 3.5 rating out of 5.

  • 53: china_beijing_beijing_hotel

  • 56: china_beijing_gloria_plaza_hotel_beijing

  • 59: china_beijing_grand_view_garden_hotel

  • 65: china_beijing_nikko_new_century_beijing_hotel

  • 72: china_beijing_new_world_hotel_jing_guang

  • 87: china_beijing_days_inn_joiest_beijing

  • 97: china_beijing_guangzhou_hotel

  • 117: china_beijing_city_hotel_beijing

  • 122: china_beijing_hebei_hotel_beijing

  • 125: china_beijing_somerset_zhongguancun

  • 130: china_beijing_hollyear_hotel_beijing

This graph shows that, lot of negative words with low rated hostels. Interstingly, tiao (Tourism Industry Association of Ontario) word is presented in 4 hostels.

In [514]:
HotelScores1 = []
Hotel1 = [53,56,59,65,72,87,97,117,122,125,130]
for hi in Hotel1:
    print(f'{hi}: {inverse_hotel[hi][0]},', end='')
    HotelScores1.append(tf_idf(hotel_vectors, hi))
print('\ndone')
select_wi1 = []
sorted_wi1 = []
tmp1 = lil_matrix((len(Hotel1),fixed_vocab_size), dtype=np.float)
for km, ks in enumerate(HotelScores1):
    for hi in ks[:8]:
        select_wi1.append(hi[1])
        if hi[1] not in sorted_wi1:
            sorted_wi1.append(hi[1])
        tmp1[km, hi[1]] = hi[7]

#select_wi=list(set(select_wi))
select_wi1 = [wi for wi,_ in Counter(select_wi1).most_common(500)]
print(len(select_wi1))

fig= plt.figure(figsize=(10,29))
ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1)
v4=hotel_vectors[:,select_wi1][Hotel1].toarray().T
plt.pcolormesh(v4, cmap=plt.cm.GnBu)
plt.yticks(np.arange(v4.shape[0]), [inverse_vocab[wi][0] for wi in csr_matrix(tmp1.sum(axis=0)).indices])
plt.xticks(np.arange(len(Hotel1)), [inverse_hotel[ki][0] for ki in Hotel1], rotation=70)
plt.colorbar()
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#FFFFFF')
plt.show()
